<dl id="n26274b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26274b">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26274b"> 274(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> son of Sorrow / d of Anguish <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n26274b"><li>FW 189.18 </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/lexg.htm#n26274b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/l39g.htm#n26274b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n26274b">MS BL 47474-79v</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:478 <a name="gd7" href="../../FF/fdra/gda.htm#gd7">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/g/gd7.htm#n26274b">Draft: I.7&sect;1.7</a>/2.7</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">When she saw her little son her tears fell fast on his baby face. &ldquo;Call him Tristram,&rdquo; she said, &ldquo;for <mark>he was born in sorrow</mark>,&rdquo; and as she spoke she fell back dead. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> For two years after his return from France, Tristram lived in Lyonesse, and then it happened that King <mark>Anguish</mark> of Ireland sent to King Mark of Cornwall to demand seven years&apos; truage that was due to him. <small> Mabel Quiller-Couch, <a name="TRIS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#TRIS"><cite title="source">Cornwall's Wonderland</cite></a> (1914) 195</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Isolde was the daughter of [King] Anguish. Sorge was, in some myths, a child of Tristan and Isolde. </mm> </dd></dl>
